{{Infobox person | name = Siegfried Rauch | image = Siegfried Rauch.jpg | birth_date = {{birth date|1932|4|2|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Landsberg am Lech]], [[Bavaria]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2018|3|11|1932|4|2|df=y}} | death_place = [[Obersöchering]], [[Bavaria]], [[Germany]] | death_cause = Heart failure from injuries sustained in a fall | occupation = Actor | years_active = 1958–2018 | spouse = Karin Rauch {{small|(until his death)}} | signature = Siegfried RauchII.jpg }} '''Siegfried Rauch''' (2 April 1932 – 11 March 2018<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/siegfried-rauch-dead-steve-mcqueens-racing-rival-le-mans-was-85-1093794</ref>) was a [[Cinema of Germany|German film]] and [[Television in Germany|television actor]]. In a career spanning over 60 years, he appeared in several international film productions and had leading roles in numerous German television productions.
==Career== Siegfried Rauch was born in [[Landsberg am Lech]], [[Upper Bavaria]]. He studied drama at the [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich]] and also attended private drama lessons. He began performing in theatres in 1958, beginning with [[Bremen]] (until 1962), and followed by [[Berlin]], [[Munich]] and [[Hamburg]].
In the 1970s, Rauch appeared in the 1970 [[Hollywood]] film ''[[Patton (film)|Patton]]'' as Captain Steiger. In ''[[Le Mans (film)|Le Mans]]'' (1971), Rauch played the race driver Erich Stahler who is [[Steve McQueen]]'s rival. In [[Samuel Fuller]]'s ''[[The Big Red One]]'', Rauch played a German army sergeant, the counterpart of Lee Marvin's character, who experiences the same events as Marvin only from a German perspective. Other Hollywood productions in which Rauch appeared were ''[[The Eagle Has Landed (film)|The Eagle Has Landed]]'' (1976) and ''[[Escape to Athena]]'' (1979).
His most famous leading role on 1970s German television was ''Thomas Lieven'' in ''[[Es muss nicht immer Kaviar sein (TV series)|Es muss nicht immer Kaviar sein]]'' (It Can't Always Be Caviar), based on the spy novel by [[Johannes Mario Simmel]]. His various other roles on television propelled his career as an actor in Germany.
From 1999 Rauch had one of the leading roles as the captain on ''[[Das Traumschiff]]'', one of the most-watched television series in Germany. In this role he was preceded by [[Heinz Weiss]] and succeeded by [[Sascha Hehn]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sascha Hehn follows Siegfried Rauch as captain of "Traumschiff"|url=https://www.derwesten.de/kultur/fernsehen/sascha-hehn-folgt-siegfried-rauch-als-traumschiff-kapitaen-id7182143.html|accessdate=10 October 2012|newspaper=Westdeutsche Allgemeine Zeitung10}}</ref> He also appeared regularly in other German TV productions, including ''[[Der Bergdoktor (2008)|Der Bergdoktor]]'', and remained active until his death.
==Personal life== Siegfried Rauch, also known as "Sigi", lived near [[Weilheim in Oberbayern|Weilheim]] in the [[Bavarian Alps]]. Rauch was married to Karin and had two sons. [[Steve McQueen]] was the godfather of his son Jakob.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/auto/fahrkultur/kultfilm-le-mans-mit-steve-mcqueen-ziggy-und-der-king-of-cool-a-1087227.html|title=Steve McQueens Kultfilm "Le Mans": "Lass die anderen quasseln"|first=Christoph|last=Stockburger|date=15 April 2016|publisher=|accessdate=12 March 2018|via=Spiegel Online}}</ref>
Rauch died on 11 March 2018 from sudden heart failure which caused him to fall down stairs at a fire station near his home in [[Obersöchering]] near Munich. He was 85 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/1.5489440|title=Nach Treppensturz: „Traumschiff“-Kapitän Siegfried Rauch ist tot|date=12 March 2018|publisher=|accessdate=12 March 2018|via=www.faz.net}}</ref><ref>https://www.tz.de/tv/siegfried-rauch-gestorben-todesursache-steht-jetzt-fest-zr-9685416.html</ref>
